4. Quantum-Resilient Cryptography Implementation

4.1 Hybrid Cryptosystem Design

4.1.1 Cryptographic Stack

```
Layer              Algorithm                    Security       Purpose
──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Key Exchange      Kyber1024 + X25519          256-bit PQ     Forward secrecy
Signatures        Dilithium5 + Ed25519        256-bit PQ     Authentication
Encryption        AES-256-GCM + ML-KEM        256-bit PQ     Confidentiality
Hashing           SHA3-512 + SPHINCS+         256-bit PQ     Integrity
Randomness        Quantum RNG + ChaCha20      ∞ entropy      Unpredictability
```

4.1.2 Key Management Architecture

```
Component                Technology                    Security Property
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Key Generation          Quantum RNG + Lattice KEM     Quantum unpredictability
Key Storage             Quantum-secure HSM            Physical quantum security
Key Distribution        QKD + Post-quantum TLS        Information-theoretic security
Key Rotation            Automated + Forward-secret     Temporal security
Key Recovery            Multi-party + Threshold        Availability + security
```

4.2 Quantum Key Distribution Implementation

4.2.1 QKD Protocol Performance

```
Protocol       Key Rate      Distance      Security         Implementation
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
BB84           1 Mbps        100 km        Information      Fiber optic
E91            500 kbps      50 km         Device-indep.    Entangled photons
MDI-QKD        100 kbps      200 km        Highest security Measurement device
Satellite QKD  10 kbps       Global        Space-based      LEO satellites
```

4.2.2 Security Proof

The security of QKD relies on fundamental quantum principles:

1. No-Cloning Theorem: |ψ⟩ cannot be copied without disturbance
2. Heisenberg Uncertainty: Measurement disturbs quantum states
3. Quantum Entanglement: EPR pairs provide secure correlation

Security Bound:

```
ε_security ≤ 2^(-s) + ε_quantum + ε_authentication
Where:
- s: Security parameter (typically 128-256)
- ε_quantum: Quantum device imperfections
- ε_authentication: Classical authentication failure
```

4.3 Performance Optimization

4.3.1 Algorithm Acceleration

```rust
// Quantum-accelerated lattice operations
impl QuantumLatticeOps {
    async fn quantum_ntt(&self, polynomial: &Polynomial) -> Result<Polynomial> {
        // Convert to quantum representation
        let quantum_state = self.encode_polynomial(polynomial).await?;
        
        // Quantum Fourier Transform (QFT) for NTT
        quantum_state.apply_qft();
        
        // Measure and decode
        let result = self.decode_polynomial(&quantum_state).await?;
        Ok(result)
    }
    
    // Achieves O(n log n) vs classical O(n^2)
}
```

